  "text": "In our experiments, the CT images are taken from four databases. The first set of CT images are from the ELCAP public lung dataset which has been produced by the Cornell University1. It contains 50 CT images of the chest which are commonly used to evaluate the performance of the computer-aided detection systems. Each of these low-dose CT images consists of about 260 slices and comprises single or multiple nodules. The spatial resolution of the images are mainly about 0.7 ×0.7 × 1.25 mm. The second used database is a freely-available set of CT images and is called as 'LIDC-IRDI' (which stands for 'Lung Image Database Consortium and the Image Database Resource Initiative') [CITATION_1] . The nodule characteristics are also available for this dataset, especially for nodules which their diameters are larger than 3 mm or smaller than 30 mm. In the experiments carried out in the present article, 800 CT images (out of total 1012 images) of this dataset have been used.",
